# Code style for the jackd2 -> Haiku port.
#
# This encodes upstream jack2's *house* C++ style (verified against linux/alsa/JackAlsaDriver.cpp,
# our primary backend model) so our new Haiku code is consistent with the surrounding engine and
# stays upstreamable. jack2 itself ships no .clang-format, and older files are inconsistent
# (some use tabs); this matches the dominant, modern backend-driver convention:
#   - 4-space indent, spaces only
#   - Linux brace style: function/class/namespace braces break to their own line;
#     control-statement braces ( ) { ) attach
#   - ~100 col practical width (kept by hand; ColumnLimit is 0 so clang-format never rewraps
#     jack2's hand-aligned parameter lists — verified to minimize churn vs the real ALSA driver)
#
# Apply ONLY to files newly authored for this port. Do NOT run clang-format -i across imported
# upstream jack2 files — that would produce a huge, non-upstreamable diff.
BasedOnStyle: LLVM
IndentWidth: 4
TabWidth: 4
UseTab: Never
ColumnLimit: 0
AccessModifierOffset: -4
BreakBeforeBraces: Linux
AllowShortFunctionsOnASingleLine: Inline
AllowShortIfStatementsOnASingleLine: Never
PointerAlignment: Left
